WEBVTT

00:05.570 --> 00:07.412
Amen, and please be seated.

00:11.256 --> 00:16.882
Now, if you have a Bible, let me invite you to turn with me to Hebrews chapter two.

00:25.051 --> 00:35.442
This morning, once again, as last week, we're taking a break from our study through the letter of Paul to the Ephesians, just to consider in light of

00:35.554 --> 00:36.115
Christmas.

00:37.417 --> 00:45.669
The fact that our Lord Jesus Christ is both fully God and fully man in one person.

00:46.450 --> 00:51.457
That God became man to bring mankind back to God.

00:52.278 --> 00:56.504
Last week we looked at John chapter 1 and the deity of Christ.

00:56.644 --> 01:03.314
In the beginning was the Word and the Word was with God and the Word was God and the Word became flesh

01:03.618 --> 01:04.640
and dwelt among us.

01:04.860 --> 01:09.327
This morning we consider the humanity of our Lord Jesus.

01:10.449 --> 01:24.912
And particularly this question, why did the eternal Son of God, creator and sustainer of the universe, take on human flesh and blood, body and soul and suffer and die?

01:25.994 --> 01:30.802
Well, He came to face everything that stands against us

01:31.330 --> 01:42.084
to face them and defeat them and to stand in victory over them as true man, to bring us with him in his victory.

01:43.005 --> 01:44.728
So what foes did he face?

01:44.788 --> 01:47.171
What victory did he win?

01:47.251 --> 01:52.278
What opposition to us did he deal with on our behalf?

01:53.299 --> 01:58.546
Let's consider that question from Hebrews chapter two, verses 14 through 18.

01:58.850 --> 02:01.213
here now the holy and inspired Word of God.

02:03.636 --> 02:27.186
Since, therefore, the children share in flesh and blood, he himself likewise partook of the same things, that through death he might destroy the one who has the power of death, that is, the devil, and deliver all those who through fear of death were subject to lifelong slavery.

02:28.514 --> 02:35.503
For surely it is not angels that he helps, but he helps the offspring of Abraham.

02:36.944 --> 02:52.684
Therefore he had to be made like his brothers in every respect so that he might become a merciful and faithful high priest in the service of God to make propitiation for the sins of the people.

02:54.486 --> 02:57.810
For because he himself has suffered when tempted,

02:58.498 --> 03:03.483
He is able to help those who are being tempted.

03:05.606 --> 03:05.966
Amen.

03:06.787 --> 03:07.828
This is God's Word.

03:08.008 --> 03:09.430
We write it on our hearts.

03:09.450 --> 03:09.950
Let's pray.

03:09.990 --> 03:21.723
Our Father in heaven, thank you that you so loved the world that you gave your only Son that whoever believes in Him should not perish but have everlasting life.

03:21.823 --> 03:28.370
And it is because Christ has died and Christ has risen to life and ascended.

03:28.674 --> 03:36.906
and it is seated at the right hand and carries with him all who belong to him by your grace through faith in Christ.

03:37.047 --> 03:38.228
Bless us with that faith.

03:38.248 --> 03:45.039
Help us to see what Jesus, what wonderful things Jesus has done for us in his name I pray.

03:46.761 --> 03:47.202
Amen.

03:48.704 --> 03:49.085
Amen.

03:49.325 --> 03:52.710
I couch this as, what enemies did he face?

03:52.770 --> 03:56.176
What opposition to us did he face?

03:56.256 --> 03:57.778
And we want to think about that

03:58.050 --> 04:00.233
Let me start this way with Sun Zu.

04:00.834 --> 04:13.693
The ancient Chinese military general and leader who wrote the art of war, and he wrote it in the fifth century, he said, if you know the enemy and you know yourself, you need not fear the result of 100 battles.

04:14.595 --> 04:20.303
If you know yourself but not the enemy, for every victory gained, you will also suffer a defeat.

04:21.104 --> 04:27.474
If you know neither the enemy nor yourself, you will succumb in every battle.

04:27.586 --> 04:34.414
thought on war is considered so wise it's part of the U.S. Marine Corps Professional Reading Program.

04:34.874 --> 04:40.801
It's recommended reading for all U.S. military intelligence personnel and if Wikipedia is to be believed.

04:41.381 --> 04:46.587
Well, it's required reading for CIA officers, but I don't know how they would know that.

04:48.149 --> 04:54.296
When you have enemies, when you have enemies, you need to know what sort of enemies you have.

04:54.656 --> 04:56.498
What kind of weapons

04:56.642 --> 04:57.543
Are they using?

04:57.583 --> 05:01.247
How can you oppose them and do so effectively?

05:02.308 --> 05:04.490
Because to be ignorant is to be defenseless.

05:05.592 --> 05:26.514
And too often Christians don't realize the kinds, the various kinds of enemies we have that stand in opposition to us, nor do we realize what Jesus has done to face them and to free us for our safety.

05:27.362 --> 05:28.183
everlastingly.

05:29.185 --> 05:33.232
The writer here points us to four things that stand in opposition to us.

05:34.454 --> 05:36.838
First, Jesus disarms the devil.

05:37.659 --> 05:38.821
The devil is against us.

05:38.901 --> 05:40.404
He's an enemy.

05:41.145 --> 05:42.447
Jesus disarms the devil.

05:42.908 --> 05:45.693
Second, you see in verse 15, he delivers us from death.

05:46.735 --> 05:51.122
Verses 16 and 17, he diverts from us the wrath of God

05:51.682 --> 05:54.807
In verse 18, he dispenses help in our temptation.

05:55.168 --> 06:00.676
Let me invite you to think about those four things Jesus does for us because Jesus is in the flesh.

06:00.757 --> 06:05.424
He shares with God's children flesh and blood.

06:06.746 --> 06:11.814
And so first, notice in verse 14, it says, Jesus disarms the devil.

06:11.875 --> 06:12.816
Look at that language.

06:13.257 --> 06:19.026
Since therefore the children share in flesh and blood, he himself likewise partook of the same things.

06:20.002 --> 06:24.389
that through death he might destroy the one who has the power of death, that is the devil.

06:25.350 --> 06:29.557
So he destroys the one who has the power of death, that is the devil.

06:30.018 --> 06:41.897
Now the writer here of course, as elsewhere in scripture, as Jesus himself confronted the devil, the Bible believes in the existence of a real devil and that he hates us.

06:42.798 --> 06:45.322
That he hates us and he hates us for a variety of reasons.

06:45.382 --> 06:47.826
He hates us because he hates God.

06:48.610 --> 06:50.432
and we are God's creatures.

06:51.113 --> 06:57.860
He hates us because he hates God and we are as men and women, boys and girls made in the image of God.

06:58.661 --> 07:15.218
We were made to represent God on the earth and though that image in us is marred, it's not absent and so he still hates us and he hates you if you are a Christian who believes in Jesus all the more because

07:15.714 --> 07:20.300
because you believe in Jesus and he stands opposed to the kingdom of Christ.

07:20.400 --> 07:23.424
And so we learn about the devil in a variety of places.

07:23.524 --> 07:35.460
In John 8, verse 44, Jesus says of him, the devil was a murderer from the beginning and has nothing to do with the truth because there is no truth in him when he lies.

07:36.141 --> 07:42.390
He speaks out of his own character for he is a liar and the father of lies.

07:43.972 --> 07:45.554
And if we don't believe,

07:45.634 --> 07:55.048
that there is a real devil, then the Bible would say to us, well, he's already then done his work on us and effectively so.

07:55.769 --> 07:59.275
Because the Bible does say that he masquerades as an angel of light.

08:00.597 --> 08:05.824
So such it is that he lies to us and deceives us and he makes us think he's not there.

08:06.385 --> 08:10.371
Or he makes us think that which is good as evil or that which is evil is good.

08:10.431 --> 08:14.898
He lies to Christians about their relationship with God.

08:15.362 --> 08:28.459
Satan will tell you, he'll work to inculcate in you a sense that even if you're a Christian, you're really just hopeless, that you're really just unloved by God.

08:29.540 --> 08:40.274
And that God has, well, God's seen enough to have enough of you and is ready to cast you aside.

08:40.994 --> 08:45.699
but you aren't hopeless and you are deeply loved and you are deeply valued by God.

08:45.739 --> 08:50.404
You're treasured by God and his love is a steadfast covenant faithful love.

08:51.405 --> 08:56.531
After all, God himself died for you upon the cross.

08:58.633 --> 09:06.942
So in what sense then here does the writer mean that the devil is destroyed or defeated here?

09:07.803 --> 09:10.386
Well, if is the apostle Peter says,

09:11.042 --> 09:27.500
the devil is still prowling around seeking someone to devour, then it's not the kind of defeat in which the devil is already cast into the lake of fire and buried in the depths of the sea, never to be seen again.

09:27.540 --> 09:36.690
But Jesus has bound him and the devil is on a leash, we might say, and his doom is sure

09:36.834 --> 09:45.084
And in the like of fire is certain, but especially here in the book of Hebrews, he is disarmed.

09:45.224 --> 09:47.707
He is defeated because he is disarmed.

09:48.248 --> 09:55.136
That is, the weapon he had against us, Jesus has taken away.

09:55.176 --> 09:58.179
That's the idea here in Hebrews too.

09:58.240 --> 10:03.666
I know we don't have the whole context and such, but in the way most important to us,

10:04.418 --> 10:08.444
Jesus made the devil impotent against us.

10:10.106 --> 10:13.611
Now I say impotent and you say, but the Bible says he has the power of death.

10:14.473 --> 10:16.856
Well, yes, but not absolute power.

10:16.916 --> 10:24.667
It's not denying that God has absolute authority over the life and death of people, right?

10:24.788 --> 10:32.018
He holds us in his hand and in him we live and move and have our being and every breath we have

10:32.322 --> 10:42.535
is by the power of Jesus who in chapter one it says he upholds the universe by the word of his power and it means he carries it along to its appointed goal.

10:42.655 --> 10:51.607
He sustains all things to the appointed end of the new heavens and new earth in all its finality and glory.

10:52.748 --> 11:00.338
But though God has control of death ultimately death being the pronouncement of God upon

11:00.482 --> 11:03.145
the sin of man, the wages of sin is death.

11:06.107 --> 11:12.393
In a sense, the devil has the power of death, subordinately, because he what?

11:12.513 --> 11:13.234
What does he do?

11:13.254 --> 11:24.024
He entices us to sin, and then he accuses us of it, and he calls for God's judgment upon us because of it.

11:25.326 --> 11:29.810
And though the devil's not infallible, often enough he has a point.

11:30.466 --> 11:48.631
Now, he is a liar, so I'm sure he says all kinds of things about you and me that aren't true, that could be easily dismissed as falsehoods, making accusations that are wild, but also the devil knows a whole lot about humanity.

11:49.393 --> 11:51.876
And some of what he says about us is true.

11:52.437 --> 11:54.900
He knows the sins we've actually committed.

11:54.980 --> 11:59.026
He knows the terrible things we've actually done or said,

11:59.458 --> 12:02.742
or failed to do and failed to say and so on.

12:04.024 --> 12:07.368
And he seeks to entice us into those things.

12:07.568 --> 12:16.659
And then when we fall, he accuses us and he says, you're worthy of death and he goes before the throne to seek our eternal judgment.

12:18.101 --> 12:22.727
He knows we deserve physical death and spiritual death and everlasting death.

12:23.988 --> 12:28.594
But through his own death, Jesus disarmed the devil.

12:29.346 --> 12:33.691
He took away this weapon used against us.

12:33.771 --> 12:40.118
And Colossians chapter 2 verses 13 to 15 helps explain this at greater length.

12:40.759 --> 12:44.162
When it says that Jesus died and God raised him from the dead.

12:44.563 --> 12:55.935
And if you were to turn over to Colossians 2 verses 13 to 15, then if you just want to listen in, as you track the passage there, you ask, what did God do for believers?

12:56.256 --> 12:58.258
Verse 13 at the end,

12:58.498 --> 13:05.747
God made us alive together with Him that is with Christ, having forgiven us all our trespasses.

13:06.849 --> 13:08.090
And how did He forgive us?

13:08.171 --> 13:14.479
Verse 14, by canceling the record of debt that stood against us with its legal demands.

13:16.661 --> 13:22.068
And how did He cancel this record of debt that stood against us with its legal demands?

13:22.950 --> 13:26.354
Well, this He set aside, nailing it to the cross.

13:27.618 --> 13:33.184
So our debt was laid to Christ's account and he paid our debt.

13:34.025 --> 13:37.409
And what was the effect of that in Colossians 2 verse 15?

13:37.750 --> 13:48.362
The effect of that was this, he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame by triumphing over them in him.

13:48.422 --> 13:55.410
Now rulers and authorities there are these technical terms for the fallen angels like the devil and his minions.

13:56.066 --> 13:57.989
Jesus took away their weapon.

13:58.490 --> 14:03.157
When they accuse us to God, Jesus says what?

14:03.317 --> 14:07.644
As our advocate, he stands in our defense and says, what?

14:08.605 --> 14:10.448
Not that they don't deserve death.

14:10.989 --> 14:11.870
He's not a liar.

14:11.911 --> 14:12.812
He knows the truth.

14:13.793 --> 14:16.758
But he says, I died their death.

14:17.880 --> 14:20.804
I suffered the wages of sin for them.

14:20.824 --> 14:24.530
I took what they deserve.

14:25.058 --> 14:27.642
so that we can sing with joyful exuberance.

14:28.503 --> 14:38.216
When Satan tempts me to despair and tells me of the guilt within, upward I look and see him there, him who who made an end of all my sin.

14:38.276 --> 14:40.759
Because the sinless Savior died.

14:41.320 --> 14:43.863
My sinful soul is counted free.

14:43.924 --> 14:51.634
For God the just is satisfied to look on him and pardon me.

14:55.202 --> 14:59.308
This is because Jesus took on flesh and blood.

14:59.468 --> 15:03.134
He shared our nature and suffered in our nature.

15:03.174 --> 15:10.965
And so, well, let's put it this way.

15:12.527 --> 15:17.114
By way of another illustration, Carl armoreding.

15:17.514 --> 15:20.098
He was watching a wild cat in a zoo.

15:20.158 --> 15:22.802
And as I stood there, he said, an attendant

15:23.042 --> 15:25.885
entered the cage through a door on the opposite side.

15:26.205 --> 15:29.569
He had nothing in his hands but a broom and carefully closing the door.

15:29.910 --> 15:32.412
He proceeded to sweep the floor of the cage.

15:33.373 --> 15:38.199
And Carl observed the worker who had no weapon to ward off the attack of the beast.

15:38.259 --> 15:48.830
In fact, when he got to the corner of the cage where the wildcat was lying, he poked the animal with the broom in the wildcat, hissed at him, and then lay down in another corner of the enclosure.

15:48.870 --> 15:52.114
And Carl remarked to the attendant,

15:52.418 --> 15:53.959
You certainly are a brave man.

15:54.020 --> 15:58.063
Now I ain't brave, he said, as he continued to sleep.

15:59.285 --> 16:01.046
Well, then that cat must be tame.

16:01.066 --> 16:03.729
No, no, he ain't tame.

16:03.769 --> 16:09.174
Well, if you aren't brave and the cat isn't tame, then I can't understand why he doesn't attack you.

16:09.514 --> 16:13.938
And the man chuckled and replied with an air of confidence, Mr.

16:14.899 --> 16:17.922
He's old and he ain't got teeth.

16:20.885 --> 16:21.906
Well, the devil's

16:22.114 --> 16:25.399
threats, have no teeth against you.

16:25.459 --> 16:45.847
His accusations don't sink into the flesh because his accusations, as it were, were dealt with by Christ upon the cross and these vicious fangs of the devil were, as it were, pulled out by Jesus upon the cross.

16:47.128 --> 16:51.314
Now, all of that isn't to say that the devil isn't

16:51.554 --> 16:54.297
prowling around like a roaring lion.

16:55.058 --> 17:11.840
That isn't to say that the devil can't in this life hurt us, lie to us, deceive us, entice us to sin or try to discourage us and make us fearful and make us believe that God doesn't love us or he won't continue to forgive us.

17:12.480 --> 17:15.925
He can cause like he did with Job, great suffering.

17:17.126 --> 17:20.050
But a believer in Jesus is safe

17:20.162 --> 17:23.627
from eternal everlasting spiritual harm.

17:27.373 --> 17:36.326
So maybe you see now why the Bible tells us to resist the devil, not to flee the devil, resist the devil.

17:36.967 --> 17:44.498
We're to flee temptation, but we're to resist the devil and James 4 says, and he will flee from you.

17:49.570 --> 17:56.100
opposed his accusations, not by arguing your innocence, but by trusting in Christ's death for you.

17:57.222 --> 18:08.018
Stand strong in the grace of the Lord, put on the armor of God, wear the belt of truth, take up the shield of faith with which you can extinguish all the flaming arrows of the evil one.

18:09.762 --> 18:22.598
Martin Luther wrote it this way, the prince of darkness grim, we tremble not for him, his rage we can endure, for lo his doom is sure, one little word shall fell him.

18:22.658 --> 18:29.506
That word above all earthly powers, no thanks to them, abideth.

18:29.707 --> 18:30.508
What word is that?

18:30.588 --> 18:36.415
That is the word made flesh who dwelt among us and disarmed the devil.

18:38.077 --> 18:39.058
Now why else did

18:39.458 --> 18:40.560
God become man.

18:40.840 --> 18:44.625
Secondly, verse 15, deliver us from the fear of death.

18:45.006 --> 18:54.019
Notice verse 15, that he did all this and delivers all those who the fear of death were subject to lifelong slavery.

18:54.039 --> 19:04.434
Neil Simon, who read the odd couple in the barefoot in the park, was asked on a talk show where they're making a lot of money concerned him.

19:04.962 --> 19:10.730
And the studio went dead silent when Simon answered, no, what does concern me is the fear of dying.

19:12.653 --> 19:14.936
Maybe you have that kind of fear.

19:16.017 --> 19:23.929
But Christians are, because of the gospel, to be freed in our heart and mind from this fear.

19:24.569 --> 19:28.235
That is we have every good reason not to fear death.

19:29.136 --> 19:33.522
And no good reason any longer to fear death.

19:35.362 --> 19:44.372
Such it is that men like Dr. B. Meyer, the great Baptist preacher a few days before his death, wrote a very different these words.

19:44.632 --> 19:50.378
I have just heard to my great surprise that I have but a few days to live.

19:51.599 --> 19:56.245
It may be that before this reaches you, I shall have entered the palace.

19:57.466 --> 19:58.287
Don't trouble the right.

19:59.468 --> 20:01.991
We shall meet in the morning.

20:03.913 --> 20:05.074
The morning of glory.

20:06.466 --> 20:16.601
When John Owen, the great Puritan lay on his death bed, his secretary wrote in his name through dictation to a friend, I am still in the land of the living.

20:17.742 --> 20:27.356
Stop said Owen, change that and say, I am yet in the land of the dying, but I hope soon to be in the land of the living.

20:28.698 --> 20:31.422
Why such competence?

20:31.442 --> 20:33.906
Well, the worst fear about death

20:34.562 --> 20:38.047
is not the act of dying or the manner of dying.

20:38.227 --> 20:41.391
The worst fear about death is not physical death.

20:41.992 --> 20:44.736
But it is what the Bible describes as second death.

20:44.976 --> 20:51.164
That is the eternal spiritual death of judgment from God.

20:51.304 --> 20:55.530
And Christ has taken away what is fearful about death.

20:55.630 --> 20:58.073
The devil can't use our sins to destroy us.

20:58.454 --> 20:59.856
Makas, sure.

20:59.896 --> 21:01.598
Taunt us, yes.

21:02.599 --> 21:04.562
See, to continue to entice us,

21:04.642 --> 21:09.231
Of course, but damn us, no.

21:09.251 --> 21:11.595
The devil can't do it.

21:12.016 --> 21:16.044
Christ bore the curse in our place.

21:17.947 --> 21:22.696
So we should say a few more words here about the fear of death leading to lifelong slavery.

21:22.736 --> 21:23.778
That's how he puts it.

21:23.899 --> 21:25.682
We through the fear of death,

21:26.466 --> 21:29.149
had lifelong slavery until we were liberated.

21:29.249 --> 21:30.370
Well, why is that?

21:30.410 --> 21:43.565
Because apart from Christ, apart from the forgiveness of sins, apart from the hope of the resurrection, the reality of eternal life and the assurance we can have of these things, apart from these things, death certainly is a thing to be feared.

21:44.446 --> 21:54.056
Because if all that is in front of you is either nothingness or an unpleasant eternity to put in mind.

21:54.076 --> 21:55.538
What's inviting about any of that?

21:57.058 --> 22:12.178
Which if you believe that either nothingness or lifelong unpleasantness or eternal unpleasantness is what stands before you and that's all the hope that you have.

22:12.719 --> 22:13.720
It's no hope at all.

22:14.961 --> 22:18.366
It means now becomes all important, right?

22:18.386 --> 22:21.490
You have to make the most of the time that you have here.

22:22.050 --> 22:25.235
You have to try perhaps to extend the time as much as possible.

22:25.275 --> 22:34.828
You have to milk it for every personal advantage in every possible pleasure because you will not have advantages and pleasures in days to come.

22:35.369 --> 22:47.346
So the fear of death for those who are outside of Christ, it sets you up for becoming enslaved to all kinds of idolatries and excesses and indulgences.

22:47.458 --> 22:51.885
So people are, some are in bondage to the clock, right?

22:52.045 --> 23:08.609
Some become enslaved to their own desires and are held captive by the things that were once freedoms, some chase after the myth of eternal youth, and will sacrifice almost anything for that insatiable idol.

23:09.511 --> 23:17.042
Some become entangled in their own possessions, owned by the very things they imagined themselves to own.

23:18.466 --> 23:21.651
The bondage that comes through the fear of death is of...

23:28.001 --> 23:29.103
Tomorrow we die.

23:29.243 --> 23:30.525
Live it up now.

23:30.585 --> 23:31.907
Live your best life now.

23:32.027 --> 23:38.197
Get all the toys now because there's nothing good beyond the grave.

23:39.319 --> 23:40.721
Well, that's one mentality.

23:41.623 --> 23:46.290
But the Bible says Christ's victory delivers us from that sort of slavery.

23:47.618 --> 23:56.689
We don't have to be held hostage by the clock or by youth or by success or by power or by status or by pleasure or by things.

23:58.271 --> 24:08.483
So Calvin says this, although we must still meet death, let us nevertheless be calm and serene in living and dying when we have Christ going before us.

24:09.805 --> 24:14.130
If anyone cannot set his mind at rest by disregarding death,

24:15.074 --> 24:19.838
That man should know that he has not yet gone far enough in the faith of Christ.

24:21.400 --> 24:22.981
Calvin is saying you're not a Christian.

24:23.742 --> 24:27.786
He's just saying you need to appreciate what you have in Christ.

24:28.567 --> 24:34.612
His liberty to look forward to even death.

24:34.973 --> 24:42.460
Death is the portal through which you pass out of a world of sin and misery and into the world of happiness and holiness and glory.

24:44.021 --> 24:45.042
So the key is that

24:45.186 --> 25:07.250
We're more than conquerors through Him who loved us to be convinced then, as the Apostle Paul says, that neither death nor life, nor angels, nor demons, nor things present, nor things future, nor any powers, nor height, nor depth, nor anything else in all creation can separate us from the love of God which is in Christ Jesus our Lord.

25:10.033 --> 25:14.578
And this is because, well, thirdly, Jesus diverts the wrath of God from us.

25:14.978 --> 25:16.080
verses 16 and 17.

25:16.100 --> 25:29.240
He disarms the devil, he releases us from the fear of death, and he diverts the wrath of God from us.

25:30.202 --> 25:36.692
Verse 16 and 17, for surely it is not angels that Jesus helps, but he helps the offspring of Abraham.

25:37.333 --> 25:40.658
Therefore, he had to be made like his brothers in every respect.

25:41.186 --> 25:47.455
so that he might become a merciful and faithful high priest in the service of God to do what?

25:48.296 --> 25:51.241
To make propitiation for the sins of the people.

25:52.042 --> 25:57.990
He's the high priest who makes propitiation for the sins of the people.

25:58.030 --> 25:58.832
What's that mean?

25:59.092 --> 25:59.953
Well, he starts here.

26:00.113 --> 26:01.415
It's not angels that he helps.

26:02.457 --> 26:03.819
It's not angels he rescues.

26:03.839 --> 26:08.786
He commands the angels to serve those Jesus is saving.

26:09.826 --> 26:13.750
But it's not the nature of an angel that Jesus took to himself.

26:14.010 --> 26:15.972
It's the children of God he rescues.

26:16.453 --> 26:24.300
Those who trusted the Messiah, the Messiah promised to Abraham, people who are children of Abraham, through faith in the Messiah.

26:24.340 --> 26:27.523
It's the nature of those brothers and sisters.

26:27.624 --> 26:34.010
You, believers in Jesus that he took to himself, was made like you in every respect.

26:34.590 --> 26:38.194
Hebrews 4 will say, but without sin, he never sinned.

26:39.202 --> 26:42.288
so that he could become a merciful and faithful high priest.

26:42.648 --> 26:44.512
Now, what is it a priest did?

26:44.632 --> 26:46.315
What did an Old Testament priest do?

26:46.395 --> 26:49.020
A priest represented the people before God.

26:49.100 --> 26:52.847
A priest offered sacrifices for atonement for the sins of the people.

26:53.408 --> 27:02.866
And a priest then assured the people that the sacrifices were acceptable and their sins were pardoned through

27:03.394 --> 27:11.822
the offering of the death of a substitute in their place, looking forward, of course, to the true lamb who takes away the sin of the world.

27:11.882 --> 27:16.106
And Jesus is that lamb, even as he is that priest.

27:17.027 --> 27:22.933
And in the language of the passage, he made in his death propitiation.

27:23.673 --> 27:32.722
That is, he turned away the wrath of God due to us for our sin by taking that wrath upon himself in our place.

27:35.522 --> 27:56.375
When I was in seminary, we took a group of teenagers north of Jackson to a little town and a small kind of a country Baptist church for their vacation Bible school to assist them in carrying out a week-long vacation Bible school.

27:56.575 --> 28:03.346
And there were going to be five daily messages, about five minutes long.

28:03.586 --> 28:10.054
And we asked my friend Keith Berger to come and share.

28:10.254 --> 28:17.983
And so Keith did and he asked for a volunteer to throw a ball as hard as he could.

28:18.063 --> 28:20.145
Let's all watch this guy throw this thing really hard.

28:20.666 --> 28:23.369
Some big, strong kid stood up and said, I'll do it.

28:23.409 --> 28:24.631
He threw it real hard.

28:24.711 --> 28:25.472
No problem.

28:25.492 --> 28:25.732
Okay.

28:26.193 --> 28:30.898
Then Keith asked for another volunteer and a little kid stood up and Keith

28:31.138 --> 28:42.814
Keith took that little kid, and he moved him a few yards away, and he had him turn his back on the big kid, and he handed the big kid the ball, and he said, now, when I tell you, throw that ball as hard as you can at that little kid.

28:43.135 --> 28:50.044
At which point, the rest of us, as youth leaders, alarm bells are going off in our heads, you can't do this.

28:50.985 --> 28:52.768
Don't do this, what are you thinking?

28:52.848 --> 28:57.234
But Keith proceeded, but before he said, throw the ball, he walked up,

28:57.922 --> 29:05.471
to the little kid, and he stood between the kid and the big kid, and he wrapped his arms around him, and he said, all right, now throw it as hard as you can.

29:05.531 --> 29:11.037
And the big kid nailed him with the ball, but the little kid was untouched.

29:12.759 --> 29:25.714
He diverted the energy of that into himself and away from the one he rescued, and so Keith turned around and said to the group, and that's the gospel.

29:25.986 --> 29:42.845
It's certainly an aspect of the truth of the gospel that God commanded our judgment because we were at fault for our rebellion and God wrapped himself up in humanity to suffer his own wrath and judgment for us.

29:43.666 --> 29:45.688
It's a glorious gospel.

29:45.788 --> 29:54.738
He took flesh and blood to function as a priest to represent us before God truly in death.

29:55.618 --> 30:02.285
and to take on God's wrath due to our humanity, our sinful humanity.

30:03.426 --> 30:08.772
And it's not that God has transformed or changed, but it is that God's wrath is satisfied.

30:09.573 --> 30:12.396
And He's satisfied by Himself and in Himself.

30:12.516 --> 30:20.685
So others have said the love of God sent the Son of God to bear the wrath of God for the people of God.

30:22.006 --> 30:25.330
And if you're not sure if you weren't one of those people of God,

30:25.410 --> 30:28.816
put your hope in Jesus, and you are.

30:28.836 --> 30:38.631
Our hell, he made his, that his heaven might be made ours, says Philip Hughes.

30:39.693 --> 30:40.835
So he disarms the devil.

30:40.895 --> 30:42.478
He delivers us from the fear of death.

30:42.518 --> 30:50.130
He diverts from us the wrath of God, and fourthly, Jesus dispenses help to us in our temptations, verse 18.

30:51.170 --> 30:52.732
We'll come to Everest 18 here a second.

30:52.973 --> 31:09.638
Even though the fear of death is taken away and we're free, some of you are saying to yourself under that discussion, yeah, but there are things about death I do fear, like how it's going to happen, how long it might take to be accomplished, all the losses that might lead up to it.

31:10.680 --> 31:17.330
Maybe it's not the actual death you're afraid of, but dying, and understandably,

31:17.986 --> 31:20.650
It's the degeneration involved.

31:20.751 --> 31:31.708
It's the loss of powers, perhaps, or the humiliation of senility or the various kinds of pains we might be called to endure.

31:31.769 --> 31:37.638
It's the sorrow of breaking away from those you love and who love you.

31:37.658 --> 31:44.850
What then do we do is we contemplate death and say that we need not fear it,

31:44.962 --> 31:52.692
What do we do in the face of all these trials and temptations and not despair as we contemplated?

31:52.853 --> 31:54.775
Well, verse 18 is here to meet us for that.

31:55.376 --> 31:56.477
It encourages us.

31:56.558 --> 32:07.672
Verse 18, for because it says, Jesus himself has suffered when tempted, he's able to help those who are being tempted.

32:08.994 --> 32:14.802
That he took on our nature not only to die, but to experience

32:15.138 --> 32:20.668
dying and all the suffering and temptations of life and death.

32:22.110 --> 32:30.685
And Jesus, the man of sorrows acquainted with death, he knows how hard it is.

32:30.745 --> 32:38.418
As mentioned earlier in the service, he knows what it is to be

32:39.074 --> 32:53.287
to be cruelly mocked and mistreated, to be abandoned by his closest companions, betrayed by one of his own disciples, to be arrested and falsely accused and abused and tortured and crucified.

32:55.029 --> 33:08.722
He knows the power of temptation in all of that, the temptation to rage against God and his providence, the temptation to be bitter against God for human death,

33:08.866 --> 33:10.268
or suffering.

33:11.209 --> 33:23.084
He knows all of that, yet without sin, but he knows the experience of it, and so he is exactly what we need because he faced these same kinds of temptations.

33:24.165 --> 33:37.202
Rick Phillips, who's now a PCA minister, says, quoting him, he says, when I was on the faculty of the United States Military Academy, I spent one summer with the Counseling Center during the training of new cadets.

33:37.506 --> 33:40.311
affectionately known as beast barracks.

33:41.292 --> 33:51.208
It's a grueling time of physical and psychological challenges under which not a few young men and women begin to crack, which is why the academy provides counselors.

33:51.949 --> 34:04.850
I was one of several officers who oversaw the center, but the counseling was done mainly by older cadets who had been through the brutal weeks of that first summer at West Point.

34:05.762 --> 34:14.813
The cadets, he said, had recently been through it themselves, and therefore were best equipped to help new cadets who were tempted to quit, go home, or otherwise fall into despair.

34:17.896 --> 34:21.060
Well, Jesus understands what you were going through.

34:21.100 --> 34:29.650
He isn't high and lifted up and untouched by the feelings of our infirmity, but Jesus humbled himself and

34:29.730 --> 34:35.317
and stooped low to condescend to add true humanity to himself.

34:35.478 --> 34:48.635
And so he's able to be a sympathetic, the writer says, and merciful priest when you cry out to him because he's been through it too.

34:49.937 --> 34:50.818
And he came to help.

34:51.980 --> 34:56.185
He is able to help as one friend helps another.

34:58.949 --> 34:59.570
And in fact,

35:00.386 --> 35:08.017
He could help any one of us in our troubles because the troubles he faced were harder than any trouble we face.

35:08.498 --> 35:08.758
C.S.

35:08.798 --> 35:14.667
Lewis put it this way, no man knows how bad he is still till he has tried very hard to be good.

35:15.629 --> 35:18.793
He's speaking of temptation, right?

35:18.913 --> 35:22.759
And he says, the silly idea is current that good people do not know what temptation means.

35:23.520 --> 35:24.722
This is an obvious lie.

35:25.904 --> 35:30.130
Only those who try to resist temptation know how strong it is.

35:31.426 --> 35:36.972
You find out the strength of a wind by trying to walk against it, not by lying down.

35:38.253 --> 35:45.181
A man who then gives in to temptation after five minutes simply does not know what it would have been like an hour later.

35:45.241 --> 35:51.228
That is why, says Lewis, bad people in one sense know very little about badness.

35:51.368 --> 35:54.371
They have lived a sheltered life by always giving in.

35:54.431 --> 36:00.818
We never find out the strength of evil, says Lewis, until we try to fight against it.

36:02.402 --> 36:15.683
And Christ, because He was the only man who never yielded to temptation, is also the only man who knows to the full what temptation means.

36:18.608 --> 36:19.550
And so we celebrate.

36:20.671 --> 36:27.282
We celebrate at Christmas, that Jesus is not only God, but He is truly human.

36:28.162 --> 36:37.194
Having disarmed the devil, delivering us from death, diverting from us the wrath of God, and dispenses help to us in our temptations.

36:37.334 --> 36:40.078
Once you put your hopes in Him.

36:40.779 --> 36:41.240
Let's pray.

36:44.764 --> 36:55.058
Our Father, thank you that this great high priest has passed through the heavens, risen from the dead, ascended, passed through the heavens now to appear in the presence of God on our behalf.

36:56.002 --> 36:58.586
We think that he always lives to intercede for us.

36:58.907 --> 37:15.433
And we thank you that the throne upon which he sits is the throne of grace, that we may come boldly, freely, even confidently to the throne of grace to receive mercy and help in our time of need.

37:15.513 --> 37:22.624
O grant us hearts that always would be looking to you and help us, we pray in Jesus' name.

37:23.565 --> 37:23.986
Amen.

37:24.642 --> 37:26.578
Amen, let's stand together and sing.

